adrienne cecile rich (may 16, 1929 â€“ march 27, 2012) was an american poet, essayist and radical feminist. she was called "one of the most widely read and influential poets of the second half of the 20th century", and was credited with bringing "the oppression of women and lesbians to the forefront of poetic discourse." her first collection of poetry, a change of world, was selected by renowned poet w. h. auden for the yale series of younger poets award. rich went on to write the introduction to the published volume. she famously declined the national medal of arts, protesting the vote by house speaker newt gingrich to end funding for the national endowment for the arts.